<paper id="1589843374"><title>Conjunctive, subset, and range queries on encrypted data</title><year>2007</year><authors><author org="Stanford, University" id="201828038">Dan Boneh</author><author org="SRI, International#TAB#" id="2131229705">Brent Waters</author></authors><n_citation>976</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>8287904</reference><reference>103647506</reference><reference>1481965140</reference><reference>1502927489</reference><reference>1512194687</reference><reference>1798609567</reference><reference>1976005800</reference><reference>1988374166</reference><reference>2051250911</reference><reference>2120976781</reference><reference>2123845384</reference><reference>2147929033</reference><reference>2149389044</reference><reference>2151471396</reference><reference>2154654620</reference><reference>2161214567</reference></references><venue id="1137528458" type="C">Theory of Cryptography Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-540-70936-7_29</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.65999">Conjunctive query</keyword><keyword weight="0.45824">Information retrieval</keyword><keyword weight="0.44301">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.53638">Range query (data structures)</keyword><keyword weight="0.45366">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.45732">Encryption</keyword><keyword weight="0.43603">Functional encryption</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We construct public-key systems that support comparison queries (x ≥ a) on encrypted data as well as more general queries such as subset queries (x∈ S). Furthermore, these systems support arbitrary conjunctive queries (P1 ∧ ... ∧ Pl) without leaking information on individual conjuncts. We present a general framework for constructing and analyzing public-key systems supporting queries on encrypted data.</abstract></paper>